oc:kn_120c49d7 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building personas or synthesizing research" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not average across different customer segments — a persona that represents everyone represents no one. Do not invent details; leave fields blank when data is missing." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Averaging erases meaningful differences between segments. Invented details undermine the credibility of research-backed personas." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_1641d70b a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building personas from research data" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before generating, verify at least 5-10 data points from a consistent segment. Structure persona: Profile (title, company size, industry, reports to), Primary JTBD, Trigger Events, Top 3 Pains, Desired Outcomes, Objections/Fears, Alternatives Considered, Key Vocabulary (exact phrases from research), How to Reach Them. Never invent details — leave blank if no data." ;
    oc:stepOrder 4 .

oc:kn_2924ab56 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When presenting research findings" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Label every insight with a confidence level: High (3+ independent sources, unprompted, cross-segment), Medium (2 sources or only prompted or single segment), Low (single source, potential outlier)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Confidence labeling prevents stakeholders from treating speculative insights the same as well-supported patterns." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_3a2ef3f8 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating personas or making research-based claims" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not build personas or draw messaging conclusions from fewer than 5 independent data points per segment." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Small samples produce misleading patterns that look actionable but aren't statistically meaningful." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_49bbcac3 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting any research engagement" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for .agents/product-marketing-context.md (or .claude/product-marketing-context.md) before asking questions. Use existing context to skip already-answered questions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Avoids redundant questions and grounds research in existing product knowledge." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_5ab06dd9 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RequiresHumanClarification ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When research context is unclear at the start" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Lead with two questions: (1) What's the goal? (messaging, personas, product gaps, churn) and (2) What do you already have? (transcripts, surveys, tickets, reviews, nothing). Follow up with target segment, product description, and desired deliverable only as needed." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Don't overwhelm with all five clarifying questions at once. Lead with goal and existing assets, then follow up progressively." .

oc:kn_608c8497 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When drawing conclusions from online research sources" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Account for source bias: online reviewers skew toward power users and strong opinions; support tickets skew toward problems not value; Reddit skews technical and skeptical versus mainstream buyers." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Unfiltered communities are valuable but systematically unrepresentative. Failing to correct for bias leads to over-indexing on vocal minorities." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_701ca8f3 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When mining G2, Capterra, App Store, or similar review sites" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For review mining, read in this order: 3-star reviews first (most honest tradeoffs), then 1-star (failure modes), then 5-star (proof points), then 4-star (buried 'I wish it could...' feedback). Competitor 4-star reviews are gold for finding gaps." ;
    oc:hasRationale "3-star reviews balance honesty with engagement. 4-star reviews of competitors reveal dissatisfaction hidden within positive sentiment." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_7ecff38c a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When extracting from interview transcripts or reviews" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Prioritize customer pains mentioned unprompted and with emotional language. Capture exact quotes rather than paraphrases — customer vocabulary is gold for copy." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Unprompted emotional responses reveal genuine priorities. Exact wording preserves the persuasive power of customer language." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_7f95f27f a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating recency of research sources" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Weight sources from the last 12 months more heavily. Use 12-24 month old data with caution. Use 2+ year old data only for baseline context." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Markets shift rapidly; a 3-year-old transcript may reflect a different product and buyer." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_aa066f7e a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When synthesizing multiple research sources into findings" ;
    oc:directiveContent "After extracting from individual assets: (1) Cluster by theme across assets, (2) Score by frequency × intensity, (3) Segment by customer profile, (4) Identify 5-10 'money quotes' per theme, (5) Flag contradictions between stated and actual behavior." ;
    oc:stepOrder 3 .

oc:kn_b1426a0c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Always, when starting any customer research engagement" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Check for product-marketing-context.md and load existing context. 2. Establish research mode (analyze existing assets vs. gather from online sources). 3. If Mode 1: apply extraction framework (JTBD, pains, triggers, outcomes, language, alternatives) then synthesize (cluster, frequency+intensity, segment, money quotes, contradictions). 4. If Mode 2: identify ICP type → select sources → extract per-source (verbatim quotes, sentiment, theme tags, profile signals) → synthesize into ranked themes. 5. Assign confidence labels to all insights. 6. Ask user which deliverable format they need." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_d4ff9e14 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When synthesizing research from multiple online sources" ;
    oc:directiveContent """## Top Themes (ranked by frequency × intensity)

### Theme 1: [Name]
**Summary**: [1-2 sentences]
**Frequency**: Appeared in X of Y sources
**Intensity**: High / Medium / Low (based on emotional language used)
**Representative quotes**:
- "[exact quote]" — [source, date]
**Implications**: What this means for messaging / product / positioning""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Frequency",
        "Implications",
        "Intensity",
        "Name",
        "Summary",
        "date",
        "exact quote",
        "source" .

oc:kn_f170b588 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When analyzing interview transcripts, surveys, support tickets, win/loss notes, or NPS responses" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For each research asset, extract: (1) Jobs to Be Done (functional, emotional, social), (2) Pain Points prioritized by unprompted emotional mentions, (3) Trigger Events that initiated the search, (4) Desired Outcomes in the customer's exact words, (5) Language and Vocabulary — exact phrases, (6) Alternatives Considered including doing nothing." ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

oc:kn_f9c35bde a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When producing persona deliverables" ;
    oc:directiveContent """## [Persona Name] — [Role/Title]
**Profile**: Title range, Company size, Industry, Reports to, Team size
**Primary Job to Be Done**: [one sentence]
**Trigger Events**: [what causes them to seek a solution]
**Top Pains**: [1-3 in their words]
**Desired Outcomes**: [success definition, measurement, perception]
**Objections and Fears**: [hesitation factors]
**Alternatives They Consider**: [competitor, DIY, do nothing]
**Key Vocabulary**: [exact phrases from research]
**How to Reach Them**: [channels, content, communities]""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Alternatives",
        "Channels",
        "Communities",
        "Company size",
        "Content",
        "Desired Outcomes",
        "Industry",
        "Key Vocabulary",
        "Objections",
        "Persona Name",
        "Primary JTBD",
        "Reports to",
        "Role/Title",
        "Team size",
        "Title range",
        "Top Pains",
        "Trigger Events" .

